Fukushima and the collapse of derivatives
CAMBRIDGE – Financial commentators have equated the Japanese earthquake, tsunami, and nuclear disaster with the role of derivatives in the 2008 financial crisis.
The similarity is quite clear: each of these activities generates large profits and involves a very low but explosive risk.
Yet, the similarity between the two types of crisis ends where the way to prevent their recurrence begins.
In the case of the Fukushima nuclear plant, a once-in-a-century flood, combined with usually harmless design flaws, caused the stoppage of cooling water circulation in the reactors and significant radiation leaks.
With regard to financial markets, an unanticipated collapse in real estate values, combined with design flaws in the derivatives and repo markets, has damaged the ability of major financial institutions to meet their debts.
Although the basic risks originate outside the systems – a tsunami for Fukushima, an overinvestment in mortgage loans for financial institutions – design flaws and a lack of luck have caused the systems to be unable to contain the damage.
In the United States, AIG, Bear Stearns and Lehman Brothers – all with significant investments in derivatives and/or repos – went bankrupt, causing a freeze in credit on the markets for several long weeks.
We now understand quite well the risks and design flaws of Fukushima.
We cannot say the same about the risks of derivatives that have shaken the global economy.
In Fukushima, workers' teams are bravely trying to stop radiation leaks.
On the contrary, for derivative products, similar efforts are misdirected and will not allow us to avoid the next financial crisis.
We are in the process of recreating similar derivative products and financial structures, on top of the same errors that are still active.
Financial actors use financial instruments to transfer risk: for example, one actor accepts the risk of euro fluctuations but does not want the risk on the yen, whereas for another, it will be the opposite.
In this case, the first promises to provide euros on June 1st, and the second promises to provide yen.
If one currency loses value relative to the other, the loser pays the difference.
Repos are financial transactions.
Financial firms sell assets, such as Treasury bills or mortgage debts, for cash and promise to repurchase these assets later, typically the following day (hence the name "repo", which is an abbreviation of the English verb repurchase – or repurchase, note from the translator).
The problem is that the cash coming from these short-term repos represents a large part of the balance sheets of the most important financial institutions, which implies that even minor financial tremors can strongly affect them.
Some institutions can then find themselves deprived of repo financing, as in 2008, and go bankrupt, like Bear Stearns.
Individually, derivative or repo transactions are scarcely blameworthy.
Each one separately legitimately transfers risk to those better able to bear it, or allows financial participation.
However, when they are used excessively by institutions that are systemically vital, they can blow up the financial system, due to its design flaws.
To this day, about 70% of the liabilities of major American financial institutions consists of very short-term loans, such as repos payable the next day.
In the United States, the main design flaws are found in bankruptcy legislation, which exempts derivatives and repos from most usual constraints in the event of bankruptcy.
For example, investors who hold derivative or repo contracts with financially weakened institutions may seize the company's assets before - and at the expense of - its normal creditors. In doing so, they can decide its fate, whereas, with a bit more time, the company in question might have survived.
Such actions ruined AIG, Bear Stearns, and others during the financial crisis.
Worse still, because investors in derivatives and repos find themselves at the head of the line for repayment in so many ways, they have less incentive to encourage market discipline by closely checking the solvency of their counterparties and carefully rationing their exposure to any single counterparty.
Typically, they will be repaid, anyway.
Certainly, someone has to be first.
Other financial actors must bear more risk because exemptions for derivative and repo market participants place them at the forefront in the event of bankruptcy.
Normally, one would expect these others to therefore have an interest in encouraging more market discipline.
But the actor that follows in line is too often the American government, as the guarantor of "too-big-to-fail" financial institutions (too important to let fail, ed.). However, the government is poorly positioned to regulate these markets on a daily basis.
It is not financially agile; it often confines itself to the regulated market; and, when economic conditions are good, no official would want to spoil the party.
The American Congress had an opportunity to address this flaw in the major overhaul of finance that it adopted last summer through the Dodd-Frank bill.
But he did not seize it.
If investors in derivatives, repo and credit-default swaps (credit event derivatives, translator's note) did not benefit from preferential treatment, they would behave differently.
First and foremost, they would more often insist that their counterparties be adequately capitalized.
They accepted the risk generated by ultra-low capitalization when it essentially involved American government money; they would be less inclined to do so if it was their own money at stake.
The public perceives Fukushima-type risks and derivative-related risks differently.
Many people fear nuclear risks, which are striking, causing a slowdown in the sector that must deal with security concerns.
However, the markets for derivatives and repos present risks that are poorly understood, difficult to communicate in the media, and complicated to debate and resolve for politicians.
During a crisis, these markets attract public attention and disdain, but when the economy stabilizes again, ordinary people lose all interest, leaving the financial sector to control its own destiny with the legislative body.
Regarding Fukushima-type risks, analysts are already discussing how nuclear power plants can be designed and built to contain risks related to earthquakes and tsunamis through passive cooling systems.
Today, it is considered possible to foresee nuclear power plants capable of keeping fuel rods cool even in the event of a complete power supply failure.
On the contrary, few significant progress has been made so far in order to prevent the damages that the priority of derivative products and repos in case of bankruptcy could cause during a new financial system crisis.
New rules are being developed, which require end users (such as oil companies using derivatives to protect themselves from unanticipated changes in the price of oil) and others to post high-quality collateral.
However, these rules do not address the main problem: the weak incentives for market discipline for major financial institutions.
It is as if we are reacting to Fukushima by better controlling gas emissions in oil extraction projects.
We should examine how to fully make derivative and repo investors bear the risk related to their decisions when they conduct transactions with financial institutions that are vital at the systemic level.
Instead, we survived the financial tsunami of 2008 only to rebuild in the same place, with the same financial flaws and according to the same defective design.
